- Docker image is analogous to classes in OOP and Docker container is analogous to objects created using the class.  
- An image registry is a centralized location for storing and sharing your container images.

Eg: DockerHub, Amazon Elastic Container Registry (ECR), Azure Container Registry (ACR), and Google Container Registry (GCR).

- The various images are present in Docker Hub([https://hub.docker.com/explore](https://hub.docker.com/explore)) while api documentation is in Docker Docs([https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/](https://docs.docker.com/reference/cli/docker/container/run/)). Getting started guide is at (https://docs.docker.com/get-started/introduction/)  
- Pulling Images, creating containers using these images, interacting with containers from other containers to get data etc. can be performed by using **Docker** commands. But as the scale of our project increases and we need quick adjustments to add new container interaction, using terminal wont workout. So we create files where we add all the instructions and use **Docker Compose.**  
- A Dockerfile is a text document that contains instructions for building a Docker image. It specifies the base image, adds files, installs dependencies, sets environment variables, exposes ports, and defines the command to run when a container is launched from the image.  
- A Docker Compose YAML file defines and configures multi-container Docker applications.It can reference Dockerfiles to build images or use pre-existing images from a registry.
